{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17643755","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17643755"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:57:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:57:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18008"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18008","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18008"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10722"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73175"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10722","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10722"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18008"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58646"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6767"},{"type":"tags","id":"7304"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24958"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24963"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73175","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73175"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following vertebrae is the hyoid bone located anterior to?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["C1","C2","C3","C4","C5"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe hyoid bone is a U-shaped bone located in the anterior neck. It is unique in that it does not articulate directly with any other bone, being suspended by muscles and ligaments. The hyoid bone is situated at the level of the \u003Cstrong\u003EC3\u003C/strong\u003E vertebra. This anatomical landmark is important for clinicians when assessing neck injuries or performing procedures such as tracheostomy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC1\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003EC2\u003C/strong\u003E are the first two cervical vertebrae, known as the atlas and axis, respectively. They are located higher in the neck and are not associated with the hyoid bone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC4\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003EC5\u003C/strong\u003E are lower cervical vertebrae, located below the level of the hyoid bone. They are not relevant to the positioning of the hyoid bone.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The hyoid bone is located at the level of the C3 vertebra.","Understanding the anatomical landmarks of the neck is crucial for clinical assessments and procedures."],"references":["Middleditch, A., \u0026 Oliver, J. (2005). Functional anatomy of the spine. Elsevier Health Sciences","Cramer, G. D., \u0026 Darby, S. A. (2013). Clinical anatomy of the spine, spinal cord, and ANS","Bogduk, N. (2016). Functional anatomy of the spine. Handbook of clinical neurology, 136, 675-688","Adigun OO, Reddy V, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Back, Spinal Cord. 2023 Jun 26. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725689","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58646"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18008"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58646","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58646"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-23T04:30:43+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-23T04:30:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10722"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions",